@{
    ViewBag.Title = "About";
}

<section class="page-card">
    <h2>About</h2>
    <h3>About this project</h3>
    <p>
        This application processes Rock-Paper-Scissors tournaments from uploaded JSON bracket files and calculates
        each round until the final champion.
    </p>
    <p>
        It started as an older WebForms technical challenge and was modernized into an ASP.NET MVC 5 application
        focused on cleaner architecture, maintainability, and a more game-oriented user experience.
    </p>
    <p>
        The current codebase separates web concerns from tournament domain logic using a dedicated core project.
    </p>

    <h3>Technology stack</h3>
    <p>
        The project currently uses:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>ASP.NET MVC 5 on .NET Framework 4.8</li>
        <li>C# with LINQ for tournament and scoring workflows</li>
        <li>Entity Framework 5 with SQL Server LocalDB for scoreboard persistence</li>
        <li>Razor views, jQuery 3.7.1, jQuery UI 1.13.2, and custom CSS for the UI</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        This is still a portfolio/challenge project, not a production system, but it follows a much more modern structure.
    </p>

    <h3>About the author</h3>
    <p>
        I am Victor Viquez Benavides, a Systems Engineer who graduated from Universidad Latina de Costa Rica in 2006.
    </p>
    <p>
        I have professional experience building web applications with Microsoft technologies, especially ASP.NET and C#.
    </p>
    <p>
        I chose this stack because it reflects the technologies I have worked with for many years, and this challenge
        became a great opportunity to modernize an older project and keep improving with newer development practices.
    </p>
</section>
